Linear Models

Much of the tutorial below is derived from: https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/linear-regression-R

Why is regression important? “Linear regression is one of the most basic statistical models out there, its results can be interpreted by almost everyone, and it has been around since the 19th century. This is precisely what makes linear regression so popular. It’s simple, and it has survived for hundreds of years. Even though it is not as sophisticated as other algorithms like artificial neural networks or random forests, according to a survey made by KD Nuggets, regression was the algorithm most used by data scientists in 2016 and 2017.”

Read in and look at ageht dataset, call it “kids” Make a plot with age on the x axis, height on the y, and show the data as points. Save the plot as “ht”

kids <- read_csv("ageht.csv")
## Rows: 12 Columns: 2
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## dbl (2): age, height
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
theme_set(theme_classic())

ht <- ggplot(kids, aes(age, height))+
  geom_point()+
  ylab("Height (cm)")+
  xlab("Age (months)")

ht

Let’s make a model to use age to predict height. To do this we will use the linear model function in R: lm(). You give lm() data in the following format: lm(target~predictor, data)

#model output = lm( target variable (Y) ~ predictor variable (X), data)
model <- lm(height~age, data = kids)

#look at the results
model
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = height ~ age, data = kids)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          age  
##      64.928        0.635
#they give you the intercept and the slope (expressed as the target variable)
#can you write a linear model from this output?


#let's put the line on our plot
#ht + geom_abline(slope = 0.635, intercept = 64.928)

#alternatively, in case you change the model or data later
#reference the model coefficients 
ht + geom_abline(slope = model$coefficients[2], intercept = model$coefficients[1], color = "blue")

Finally, there is a tidy way to look at the line fit as well. The function add_predictions() take our model as input and generates predicted y values for each x automatically. This is especially helpful if our model prediction isn’t just a straight line.

kids <- kids %>%
  add_predictions(model)

ggplot(kids, aes(age, height))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

How well does this line represent the relationship?

#summary() will give you a bunch of informaton about the model
#let's look at what is there and see if we can decide
#if the model is good
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = height ~ age, data = kids)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.27238 -0.24248 -0.02762  0.16014  0.47238 
## 
## Coefficients:

## (Intercept)  64.9283     0.5084  127.71  < 2e-16 ***
## age           0.6350     0.0214   29.66 4.43e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.256 on 10 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.9888, Adjusted R-squared:  0.9876 
## F-statistic:   880 on 1 and 10 DF,  p-value: 4.428e-11
#Summary gave us some information about the residuals
#but we can also plot them to look for patterns
kids <- kids %>%
  add_residuals(model)

ggplot(kids, aes(age, resid))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)

Okay, now try for yourself using the pressure dataset. read it in as ‘p’ plot temp (x) vs pressure (y) as points create a linear model of the relationship between pressure and temperature add predictions and residuals to ‘p’ plot the model predictions as a line with the points generate a summary of the linear model plot the residuals

Is this a good fit? Explain.

#read file
p <- read_csv("pressure.csv")
## Rows: 10 Columns: 2
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## dbl (2): Temperature, Pressure
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
#plot
ggplot(p, aes(Temperature, Pressure))+
  geom_point()

#fit and save model
pm <- lm(Pressure~Temperature, p)

#add model predictions and residuals to the data
p <- p %>%
  add_predictions(pm) %>%
  add_residuals(pm)

#add line to plot
ggplot(p, aes(Temperature, Pressure))+
  geom_point()+
  geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

#how good is the fit?
summary(pm)
##

  geom_point()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0)

One way to create a model that would fit these data is given below. Basically, if we take the log10 of Pressure and plot that, it looks linear. So we can fit a linear model to the log10 of Pressure.

We can use that model to generate predictions, which will predic log10(pressure), so to get just the regular pressure, we can do 10^prediction. If you used log() instead of log() the inverse would be exp().

p2 <-mutate(p, logp = log10(Pressure))

p2model <- lm(logp~Temperature, p2)

p2 <- p2 %>% add_predictions(p2model)

#show the fit with the logged pressure values
ggplot(p2, aes(Temperature, logp))+
    geom_point()+
    geom_line(aes(y = pred), color = "red")

#take 10^ of the modeled pressure values to get regular pressure
ggplot(p2, aes(Temperature, Pressure))+
     geom_point()+
     geom_line(aes(y = 10^pred), color = "red")

A quick way to explore linear relationships with ggplot

kids %>% ggplot(aes(age, height))+
  geom_point()+
  stat_smooth(method = 'lm')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Now for an example of why it is so important to plot our data, not just run models/stats on it.

We will first read the DatasaurusDozen file, and then perform some statistics on the groups within.

From this analysis, what can you say about the 12 groups in the data?

DD <- read_tsv("DatasaurusDozen.tsv")
## Rows: 1846 Columns: 3
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: "\t"
## chr (1): dataset
## dbl (2): x, y
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
unique(DD$dataset)
##  [1] "dino"       "away"       "h_lines"    "v_lines"    "x_shape"   
##  [6] "star"       "high_lines" "dots"       "circle"     "bullseye"  
## [11] "slant_up"   "slant_down" "wide_lines"
DD %>% group_by(dataset) %>%
  summarize(meanx = mean(x), 
            meany = mean(y),
            sdx = sd(x), 
            sdy = sd(y),
            R2lm = summary(lm(y~x))$r.squared,
            corrxy = cor(x,y))
